9nagement linguistique dans le monde - Cameroun]\n* [http://www.translationdirectory.com/article419.htm Leinyui, Usmang Salle. n.d. \"Bilingualism.\" TranslationDirectory.com] (article focuses on Cameroon)\n* [http://www.sprak.gu.se/digitalAssets/1328/1328399_no-7_final-multilingual-cameroon-081101.pdf Rosendal, Tove. 2008. \"Multilingual Cameroon: Policy, Practice, Problems and Solutions.\" University of Gothenburg, Africana Informal Series, No. 7]\n\n{{Languages of Cameroon}}\n{{Africa in topic|Languages of}}\n{{Niger-Congo branches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Languages Of Cameroon}}\n[[Category:Languages of Cameroon| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Languages of\n| country     = Cameroon\n| official    = [[French Language|French]], [[English language|English]]\n| national    = 55 [[Afro-Asiatic languages]], two [[Nilo-Saharan languages]], and 173 [[Niger\u2013Congo languages]]\n| extralabel  = [[Lingua franca]](s)\n| extra       = [[African French|French]], [[English language|English]], [[Camfranglais]], [[Cameroonian Pidgin English]]\n| sign        = [[American Sign Language]] ([[Francophone African Sign Language]])\n}}\n{{Culture of Cameroon}}\n[[File:Francophonie au Cameroun en 2005 selon l'OIF.png|thumb|right|300px|Knowledge of French in Cameroon in 2005, according to the [[Francophonie|OIF]].<ref>[http://20mars.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/FICHE_03_Nombre_de_francophones.pdf Estimation of number of French speakers worldwide.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120012438/http://20mars.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/FICHE_03_Nombre_de_francophones.pdf |date=2010-01-20 }}, Francophonie.org</ref> In 2005 18% of the population were \"real\" French speakers and another 26.8% were \"partial French speakers\". Both figures are estimations.]]\n[[File:Langues du Cameroun Carte.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of Cameroon's [[official language]]s. Blue: French speaking regions and countries. Red: English speaking regions and countries. Grey: Trilingual [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] and French speaking country ([[Equatorial Guinea]]).]]\n[[File:Nigeria Benin Cameroon languages.png|thumb|280x280px|Map of the region's [[indigenous language]]s.]]\n'''[[Cameroon]]''' is home to nearly 250 languages.<ref>Kouega, Jean-Paul. 'The Language Situation in Cameroon', Current Issues in Language Planning, vol. 8/no. 1, (2007), pp. 3-94.</ref> These include 55 [[Afroasiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic languages]], two [[Nilo-Saharan languages]], four [[Ubangian languages]], and 169 [[Niger\u2013Congo languages]]. This latter group comprises one [[Senegambian languages|Senegambian language]] ([[Fula language|Fulfulde]]), 28 [[Adamawa languages]], and 142 [[Benue\u2013Congo languages]] (130 of which are [[Bantu languages]]).<ref>Neba 65.</ref>\n[[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]] are official languages, a heritage of Cameroon's [[colonialism|colonial]] past as a colony of both [[France]] and the [[United Kingdom]] from 1916 to 1960. Eight out of the ten [[regions of Cameroon]] are primarily [[francophone]], representing 83% of the country's population, and two are [[anglophone]], representing 17%. The anglophone proportion of the country is in constant regression, having decreased from 21% in 1976 to 20% in 1987 and to 17% in 2005, and is estimated at 16% in 2015 (whose fourth census should take place in 2015).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsducamer.com/index.php/economie/item/4683-confidences-sur-la-pr%C3%A9paration-du-4e-recensement-g%C3%A9n%C3%A9ral-de-la-population-du-cameroun |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002157/http://newsducamer.com/index.php/economie/item/4683-confidences-sur-la-pr%C3%A9paration-du-4e-recensement-g%C3%A9n%C3%A9ral-de-la-population-du-cameroun |archivedate=2016-03-04 }} </ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cameroon.africadata.org/fr/DataAnalysis |title=Portail de donn\u00e9es du Cameroun, Analyse de Donn\u00e9es |website=Cameroon.africadata.org |accessdate=2017-08-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225101243/http://cameroon.africadata.org/fr/DataAnalysis |archivedate=2017-02-25 }}</ref>\n\nThe nation strives toward [[bilingual]]ism, but in reality very few Cameroonians speak both French and English, and many speak neither.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} The government has established several bilingual schools in an effort to teach both languages more evenly; however, in reality most of these schools separate the anglophone and francophone sections and therefore do not provide a true bilingual experience.<ref>DeLancey and DeLancey 51.</ref> Cameroon is a member of both the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and La [[Francophonie]]. [[German language|German]], the country's official language during the German colonial period until World War I, has nowadays almost entirely yielded to its two successors. However, as a foreign language subject German still enjoys huge popularity among pupils and students, with 300,000 people learning or speaking German in Cameroon in 2010. Today, Cameroon is one of the African countries with the highest number of people with knowledge of German.<ref>[http://www.dw.com/de/wenn-deutsch-gleich-zukunft-hei\u00dft/a-5070255 \"Wenn Deutsch gleich Zukunft hei\u00dft\"], Dw.com, 29 Nov. 2010</ref>\n\nMost people in the English-speaking [[Northwest Province (Cameroon)|Northwest]] and [[Southwest Province (Cameroon)|Southwest]] provinces speak [[Cameroonian Pidgin English]] as a lingua franca.<ref>DeLancey and DeLancey 220.</ref> [[Fula language|Fulfulde]] serves the same function in the north, and [[Ewondo language|Ewondo]] in much of the [[Centre Province (Cameroon)|Center]], [[South Province (Cameroon)|South]], and [[East Province (Cameroon)|East]] provinces.<ref name=\"DeLancey and DeLancey 192\">DeLancey and DeLancey 192.</ref>\n[[Camfranglais]] (or Frananglais) is a relatively new pidgin communication form emerging in urban areas and other locations where Anglophone and Francophone Cameroonians meet and interact. Popular singers have used the hybrid language and added to its popularity.<ref>DeLancey and DeLancey 131.</ref>\n\nEducation for the deaf in Cameroon uses [[American Sign Language]], introduced by the deaf American missionary [[Andrew Foster (educator)|Andrew Foster]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nThere is little literature, radio, or television programming in native Cameroonian languages. Nevertheless, many Cameroonian languages have alphabets or other writing systems, many developed by the Christian missionary group [[SIL International]], who have translated the Bible, Christian hymns, and other materials. The [[General Alphabet of Cameroon Languages]] was developed in the late 1970s as an orthographic system for all Cameroonian languages.\n\nIn the late 19th century, the [[Bamum script]] was developed by Sultan [[Ibrahim Njoya]] to write the [[Bamum language]].<ref name=\"DeLancey and DeLancey 192\"/>\n\n== Official languages ==\n\n{| \n|- style=\"vertical-align:text-top;\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"margin:0px;\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|R.|Rank}}\n|-\n| 1\n|-\n| 2\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | <br>\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable alternance\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+ Literacy in official languages<br />according to the 2005 census<ref name=\"rp2005-alpha-p220\">{{cite web|language=fr|url=http://www.bucrep.cm/index.php/fr/component/phocadownload/category/42-analyses-thmatiques?download=90:tome-2-scolarisation-instruction-alphabtisation-cameroun-volume-IV-Alphab\u00e9tisation-et-fr\u00e9quentation-scolaire|title=Troisi\u00e8me RGPH (2005) - Alphab\u00e9tisation|page=220 |website=Bucrep.cm|accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref><br />(population of age 12 and above)\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|Language|Literacy language (reading and writing)}} !! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|%|Percent}} !! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|<nowiki>#</nowiki>|Number}}\n|-\n| align=left | [[French language|French]] (total) || 57.6 || {{formatnum:6405981}}\n|-\n| align=left | [[English language|English]] (total) || 25.2 || {{formatnum:2802794}}\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[French language|French]] only'' || ''46.0'' || ''{{formatnum:5112479}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[English language|English]] only'' || ''13.6'' || ''{{formatnum:1509292}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]]'' || ''11.6'' || ''{{formatnum:1293502}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''Neither [[French language|French]] nor [[English language|English]]'' || ''28.8'' || ''{{formatnum:3199221}}''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" align=left | Total || style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | 100,00 || style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{formatnum:11114495}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.odsef.fss.ulaval.ca/sites/odsef.fss.ulaval.ca/files/rr_cameroun_19602005_final2_web.pdf|format=PDF|title=Les dynamiques d\u00e9molinguistiques au Cameroun de 1960 \u00e0 2005|page=77|website=Odsef.fss.ulaval.ca|accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n|}\n|}\n\n{| \n|- style=\"vertical-align:text-top;\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"margin:0px;\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|R.|Rank}}\n|-\n| 1\n|-\n| 2\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| -\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | <br>\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable alternance\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+ Literacy in official languages<br />according to the 2005 census<ref name=\"rp2005-alpha-p220\"/><br />(population of age 15 and above)\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|Language|Literacy language (reading and writing)}} !! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|%|Percent}} !! style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{abbr|<nowiki>#</nowiki>|Number}}\n|-\n| align=left | [[French language|French]] (total) || 57 || {{formatnum:5566339}}\n|-\n| align=left | [[English language|English]] (total) || 25 || {{formatnum:2448914}}\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[French language|French]] only'' || ''45'' || ''{{formatnum:4401333}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[English language|English]] only'' || ''13'' || ''{{formatnum:1283908}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]]'' || ''12'' || ''{{formatnum:1165006}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''Neither [[French language|French]] nor [[English language|English]]'' || ''30'' || ''{{formatnum:2909664}}''\n|-\n| align=left | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''Undetermined'' || ''1'' || ''{{formatnum:85568}}''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" align=left | Total || style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | 100,00 || style=\"background-color:#FFD700;\" | {{formatnum:9845479}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bucrep.cm/index.php/en/recensements/3eme-rgph/resultats/47-3eme-rgph/volume-ii--analyses-thematiques |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715225446/http://www.bucrep.cm/index.php/en/recensements/3eme-rgph/resultats/47-3eme-rgph/volume-ii--analyses-thematiques |archivedate=2015-07-15 }} </ref>\n|}\n|}\n\nLiteracy in French for individuals of age 12 and above rose from 41.3% to 57.6%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.erudit.org/livre/aidelf/2012/004097co.pdf|format=PDF|title=Dynamique des langues nationales et officielles au Cameroun de 1987 \u00e0 2005|page=13|website=Erudit.org|accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> between 1987 and 2005 while that of English rose from 13.4% to 25.3%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.erudit.org/livre/aidelf/2012/004097co.pdf|format=PDF|title=Dynamique des langues nationales et officielles au Cameroun de 1987 \u00e0 2005|page=12|website=Erudit.org|accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref> The global proportion of individuals literate in official languages has thus markedly increased between 1987 and 2005, rising from 53.3% to 71.2%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.odsef.fss.ulaval.ca/sites/odsef.fss.ulaval.ca/files/rr_cameroun_19602005_final2_web.pdf|format=PDF|title=Les dynamiques d\u00e9molinguistiques au Cameroun de 1960 \u00e0 2005 : un \u00e9clairage \u00e0 travers les donn\u00e9es des recensements|page=56|website=Odsef.fss.ulaval.ca|accessdate=2017-08-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the probability to be literate in French while being anglophone was 0.46 while that of being literate in English while being francophone was 0.20, resulting from the predominant status of the French language in Cameroon as a whole.\n\n==Indigenous languages==\n{{refimprove|date=December 2014}}\nSome of the common languages native to Cameroon include:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Name !! Speakers\n|-\n|[[Abo language|Abo]] ||\n|-\n|[[Afade language|Afade]] ||\n|-\n|[[Aghem language|Aghem]] ||\n|-\n|[[Akoose language|Akoose]] ||\n|-\n|[[Akum language|Akum]] ||\n|-\n|[[Ambele language|Ambele]] ||\n|-\n|[[Chadian Arabic|Arabic, Chadian]] || 171,000\n|-\n|[[Atong language (Grassfields Bantu)|Atong]] ||\n|-\n|[[Awing language|Awing]] ||\n|-\n|[[Babanki language|Babanki]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bafanji language|Bafanji]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bafaw-Balong language|Bafaw-balong]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bafia language|Bafia]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bafut language|Bafut]] ||\n|-\n|[[Baka language|Baka]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bakoko language|Bakoko]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bakole language|Bakole]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bakundu-Balue language|Bakundu-balue]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bakweri language|Bakweri]] ||\n|-\n|[[Baldamu language|Baldamu]] ||4\n|-\n|[[Balo language|Balo]] ||\n|-\n|[[Balundu-Bima language|Balundu-bima]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bamali language|Bamali]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bambalang language|Bambalang]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bambili language|Bambili]] ||\n|-\n|[[Bamenyam language|Bamenyam]] |