y of the Republic of Cameroon,'' 3rd ed. Bamenda: Neba Publishers.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=CM ''Ethnologue'' page on Languages of Cameroon]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070706105059/http://www.panafril10n.org/wikidoc/pmwiki.php/PanAfrLoc/Cameroon PanAfriL10n page on Cameroon]\n* [http://www.tlfq.ulaval.ca/axl/afrique/cameroun.htm Am\u00e9nagement linguistique dans le monde - Cameroun]\n* [http://www.translationdirectory.com/article419.htm Leinyui, Usmang Salle. n.d. \"Bilingualism.\" TranslationDirectory.com] (article focuses on Cameroon)\n* [http://www.sprak.gu.se/digitalAssets/1328/1328399_no-7_final-multilingual-cameroon-081101.pdf Rosendal, Tove. 2008. \"Multilingual Cameroon: Policy, Practice, Problems and Solutions.\" University of Gothenburg, Africana Informal Series, No. 7]\n\n{{Languages of Cameroon}}\n{{Africa in topic|Languages of}}\n{{Niger-Congo branches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Languages Of Cameroon}}\n[[Category:Languages of Cameroon| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dz3", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added ref to ethnologue and changed phrasing about the total number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Languages_of_Cameroon"}
{"title_page": "\u014ctori-class torpedo boat", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=yes}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Kiji_1937.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Kiji'' 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=\n|Builders=\n|Operators=\n|Class before=[[Chidori-class torpedo boat|''Chidori'' class]]\n|Class after={{sclass-|Matsu|destroyer|4}} (small destroyers)\n|Subclasses=\n|Cost=\n|Built range=1934-1937\n|In service range=\n|In commission range=1936-1946\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=16\n|Total ships completed=8\n|Total ships cancelled=8\n|Total ships active=\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=7\n|Total ships retired=1\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type=[[Torpedo boat]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=*840 tons standard\n*960 tons for battle condition<ref>''\u014ctori'' was 1,012 tons for battle condition.</ref>\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length=*{{convert|88.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} full\n*{{convert|85.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}} waterline\n|Ship beam={{convert|8.18|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft={{convert|2.76|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth={{convert|4.85|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=*2 \u00d7 Kampon water tube boilers\n*2 \u00d7 Kanpon impulse turbines\n*2 \u00d7 shafts, {{convert|19000|shp|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed={{convert|30.5|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|4000|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|14|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=129\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*''\u014ctori'', 1936\n*3 \u00d7 [[12 cm 11th Year Type naval gun|{{convert|120|mm|in|abbr=on}}/45]] 11th Year Type guns (3\u00d71)\n*1 \u00d7 [[Vickers 40 mm AA]] gun<ref>''Kari'' was equipped 2 \u00d7 [[Type 96 25&nbsp;mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96 {{convert|25|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] AA guns.</ref>\n*1 \u00d7 11 mm [[machine gun]]\n*3 \u00d7 Type 94 Torpedo tubes (1\u00d73)\n*3 \u00d7 6th Year Type torpedoes\n*2 \u00d7 [[Paravane (weapon)|paravane]]s\n*''Hiyodori'', August 1944\n*2 \u00d7 12&nbsp;cm/45 (4.7-inch) 11th Year Type guns (2\u00d71)\n*11 \u00d7 [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96 25 mm AA guns]]\n*3 \u00d7 Type 94 Torpedo tubes (1\u00d73)\n*3 \u00d7 6th Year Type torpedoes\n*48 \u00d7 [[depth charge]]s\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''''\u014ctori''-class torpedo boat'''|\u9d3b\u578b\u6c34\u96f7\u8247|\u014ctori-gata suiraitei}} were a class of eight fast [[torpedo boat]]s of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] built before and operated during [[World War II]].\n\n==Development==\nTo circumvent the terms of the 1930 [[London Naval Treaty]], which limited its total destroyer tonnage the Imperial Japanese Navy designed the {{sclass-|Chidori|torpedo boat|4}} torpedo boat, but planned to arm it with half the armament of a {{sclass-|Fubuki|destroyer|4}} destroyer. The resultant design was top-heavy and unstable, resulting in the 1934 ''Tomozuru'' Incident, in which one of the ''Chidori''-class vessels capsized. The subsequent investigation revealed the fundamental design flaw, and the four vessels in the class which had been completed were extensively rebuilt, and the remaining sixteen vessels projected were cancelled in favor of a new design which would address these design issues from the beginning. Sixteen ''\u014ctori''-class vessels were ordered in the 1934 [[2nd Naval Armaments Supplement Programme]], of which eight were completed between 1936 and 1937. The remaining eight were cancelled in favor of building additional [[submarine chaser]]s.<ref name=\"Stille\">{{cite book |last1=Stille |first1=Mark |title=Imperial Japanese Navy Antisubmarine Escorts 1941\u201345 |date=2017 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978 1 4728 1817 1 |pages=18\u201320}}</ref><ref>The cancelled units, Torpedo boats #13 to #20 under the 1934 Programme, were projected to have been named ''Hatsutaka'', ''Aotaka'', ''Wakataka'', ''Kumataka'' (\"bear hawk\"), ''Yamadori'' (\"mountain bird\"), ''Mizudori'' (\"water fowl\"), ''Umidori'' (\"seabird\") and ''Komadori''; however, no contracts were placed by the time the order was changed in 1937 in favour of Submarine chasers #4 to #11.</ref>\n\n==Design==\nBenefiting from the redesign of the ''Chidori''-class, the ''\u014ctori''-class had a slightly longer hull with an increased beam. The bridge structure was also lower than on the ''Chidori''-class to help keep the center-of-gravity low. Two [[Kampon]] geared turbines powered by two Kampon water-tube boilers produced a total of {{convert|19000|shp|kW}}, which gave the ships more power than the ''Chidori''-class, and thus a slightly higher maximum speed of {{convert|30.0|kn|mph km/h|lk=in}}<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nThe armament of the ''\u014ctori''-class was almost the same as for the rebuilt ''Chidori''-class with a [[main battery]] of three single [[12 cm/45 3rd Year Type naval gun]]s which to elevate to 55 degrees for a limited anti-aircraft capability. The torpedo mount was upgraded from a twin to a triple torpedo launcher, and a single Type 94 [[depth charge]] launcher was carried. However, anti-aircraft weaponry was only a single license-built Vickers [[QF 2 pounder naval gun#QF 2-pounder Mark II|40 mm (2 pounder pom pom)]].<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nDuring the [[Pacific War]], in 1944 survivors had the aft gun removed, and up to three twin-mount and five single-mount [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|''Type 96'' 25mm AA gun]]s were installed as well as a Type 22 and a Type 13 radar. The number of depth charges was increased to 48.<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\n==Operational service==\nThe ''\u014ctori''-class were used extensively from the start of the Pacific War to escort invasion convoys to the Philippines, Dutch East Indies and the Solomon Islands. {{ship|Japanese torpedo boat|Hiyodori||2}} sank the {{USS|Amberjack|SS-219}} during the [[Solomon Islands campaign]] on 16 February 1943. Seven of the eight ships in the class were sunk by submarines or air attack in the Pacific or the [[South China Sea]] and only\n{{ship|Japanese torpedo boat|Kiji|1937|2}} survived to the end of the war.\n\n==Ships in class==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"}\n| width=\"15%\" | '''Ship''' and meaning\n| width=\"12%\" bgcolor= | '''Builder'''\n| width=\"10%\" bgcolor= | '''Laid down'''\n| width=\"10%\" bgcolor= | '''Launched'''\n| width=\"10%\" bgcolor= | '''Completed'''\n| width=\"24%\" bgcolor= | '''Fate'''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat \u014ctori (1935)|''\u014ctori'']]|\u9d3b}}<br>(\"stork\")\n|[[Maizuru Naval Arsenal]]\n|8 November 1934\n|25 April 1935\n|10 October 1936\n| Sunk 12 June 1944 by aircraft of Task Force 58 NW of [[Saipan]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Hiyodori|''Hiyodori'']]|\u9d6f}}<br>(\"brown-eared bulbul\")\n|[[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima Shipyards]]\n|26 November 1934\n|25 October 1935\n|20 December 1936\n| Sunk 17 November 1944 by {{USS|Gunnel|SS-253|6}} in [[South China Sea]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Hayabusa (1935)|''Hayabusa'']]|\u96bc}}<br>(\"peregrine falcon\")\n|[[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries|Yokohama Dock Company]]\n|19 December 1934\n|28 October 1935\n|7 December 1936\n| Sunk 24 September 1944 by aircraft in [[Sibuyan Sea]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Kasasagi (1935)|''Kasasagi'']]|\u9d72}}<br>(\"magpie\")\n|[[Hitachi Zosen Corporation|\u014csaka Iron Works]]\n|4 March 1935\n|18 October 1935\n|15 January 1937\n| Sunk 26 September 1943 by {{USS|Bluefish|SS-222|6}} in [[Flores Sea]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Kiji (1937)|''Kiji'']]|\u96c9}}<br>(\"pheasant\")\n|[[Mitsui Engineering & Shipbuilding|Mitsui Engineering & Shipbuilding, Tamano]] \n|24 October 1935\n|26 January 1937\n|31 July 1937\n| Surrendered to [[Soviet Union]] on 3 October 1947 at [[Nakhodka]]. Renamed '''''Vnimatel'nyy'''''. Decommissioned on 31 October 1957.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Kari (1937)|''Kari'']]|\u96c1}}<br>(\"wild goose\")\n|Yokohama Dock Company\n|11 May 1936\n|20 January 1937\n|20 September 1937\n| Sunk 16 July 1945 by {{USS|Baya|SS-318|6}} at [[Java Sea]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Sagi (1937)|''Sagi'']]|\u9dfa}}<br>(\"snowy heron\")\n|[[IHI Corporation|Harima Shipyards]]\n|20 May 1936\n|30 January 1937\n|31 July 1937\n| Sunk 8 November 1944 by USS ''Gunnel'' W of [[Luzon]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|[[Japanese torpedo boat Hato (1937)|''Hato'']]|\u9ce9}}<br>(\"dove\")\n|Ishikawajima Shipyards\n|28 May 1936\n|25 January 1937\n|7 August 1937\n| Sunk 16 October 1944 by aircraft at [[Hong Kong]].\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Hatsutaka''|\u521d\u9df9}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Aotaka''|\u84bc\u9df9}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Wakataka''|\u82e5\u9df9}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Kumataka''|\u718a\u9df9}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Yamadori''|\u5c71\u9ce5}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Mizutori''|\u6c34\u9ce5}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Umidori''|\u6d77\u9ce5}}<br/>{{nihongo|''Komadori''|\u99d2\u9ce5}}\n|colspan=4 align=center | Cancelled in 1937.\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Collection of writings by Sizuo Fukui Vol.5, Stories of Japanese Destroyers'', K\u014djinsha (Japan) 1993, {{ISBN|4-7698-0611-6}}\n*''Model Art Extra No.340, Drawings of Imperial Japanese Naval Vessels Part-1'', Model Art Co. Ltd. (Japan), October 1989, Book code 08734-10\n*''The Maru Special, Japanese Naval Vessels No.39 Japanese Torpedo Boats'', Ushio Shob\u014d (Japan), May 1980, Book code 68343-40\n\n==External links==\n*[http://homepages.fh-giessen.de/~hg6339/data/jp/torpedoboats/1934_ctb_otori-type.htm Japanese \"Otori\" Class Torpedo Boats]\n*[http://www.combinedfleet.com/lancers.htm Japanese Torpedo Boats: Tabular Movement Records (TROMs)]\n*[http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/japanese_torpedo_boats.htm Japanese Torpedo Boats]\n\n{{Japanese torpedo boats in WWII}}\n{{WWII Japanese Ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otori Class Torpedo Boat}}\n[[Category:World War II naval ships of Japan]]\n[[Category:\u014ctori-class torpedo boats| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=yes}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Kiji_1937.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Kiji'' 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=\n|Builders=\n|Operators=\n|Class before=[[Chidori-class torpedo boat|''Chidori'' class]]\n|Class after={{sclass-|Matsu|destroyer|4}} (small destroyers)\n|Subclasses=\n|Cost=\n|Built range=1934-1937\n|In service range=\n|In commission range=1936-1946\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=16\n|Total ships completed=8\n|Total ships cancelled=8\n|Total ships active=\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=7\n|Total ships retired=1\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type=[[Torpedo boat]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=*840 tons standard\n*960 tons for battle condition<ref>''\u014ctori'' was 1,012 tons for battle condition.</ref>\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length=*{{convert|88.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} full\n*{{convert|85.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}} waterline\n|Ship beam={{convert|8.18|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft={{convert|2.76|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth={{convert|4.85|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=*2 \u00d7 Kampon water tube boilers\n*2 \u00d7 Kanpon impulse turbines\n*2 \u00d7 shafts, {{convert|19000|shp|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed={{convert|30.5|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|4000|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|14|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=129\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to